# Authentication

This project ships with [django-allauth](https://docs.allauth.org/) configured for:

- **Email-only login** — no usernames, `email` is the `USERNAME_FIELD`.
- **Mandatory email verification** for signups.
- **MFA** with TOTP authenticator apps + recovery codes (`MFA_SUPPORTED_TYPES`).
- **Argon2id** as the primary password hasher (configured globally; PBKDF2 retained for legacy hashes).
- **Rate limiting** on failed logins (5 attempts / 5 minutes by default).

## Routes

| Path | What it's for |
| --- | --- |
| `/accounts/login/` | Sign in (server-rendered) |
| `/accounts/signup/` | Create an account |
| `/accounts/password/reset/` | Forgot password |
| `/accounts/mfa/totp/activate/` | Enable TOTP |
| `/accounts/mfa/recovery-codes/` | View / regenerate recovery codes |
| `/{{ '{' }}{{ '{' }}DJANGO_ADMIN_URL{{ '}' }}{{ '}' }}` | Django admin (defaults to `/admin/`) |
{%- if bakery.has_frontend_spa %}
| `/_allauth/browser/v1/auth/login` | JSON login (headless, for the SPA) |
| `/_allauth/browser/v1/auth/signup` | JSON signup |
| `/_allauth/browser/v1/auth/2fa/authenticate` | MFA challenge |
| `/_allauth/browser/v1/auth/password/reset` | Trigger password reset |
{%- endif %}

## MFA enrolment

1. User signs in with email + password.
2. They visit `/accounts/mfa/totp/activate/`, scan the QR code with an authenticator app, and enter the resulting 6-digit code.
3. They view + save their **recovery codes** at `/accounts/mfa/recovery-codes/`.
4. Subsequent logins challenge for the TOTP code after password validation.

## Admin hardening

- Always require MFA for `is_staff` users — enforce via signal or admin-only middleware.
- Move `/admin/` to a non-obvious URL via `DJANGO_ADMIN_URL` env.
- IP-allowlist the admin via your edge proxy (Traefik / Cloudflare / nginx) in production.

{%- if bakery.has_frontend_spa %}

## SPA authentication flow

The frontend talks to `/_allauth/browser/v1/...` JSON endpoints. Sessions are cookie-based —
the SPA just needs to call the login endpoint, and the resulting `sessionid` cookie carries
the auth state for all subsequent requests.

Example login (TypeScript fetch):

```ts
async function login(email: string, password: string) {
  const r = await fetch("/_allauth/browser/v1/auth/login", {
    method: "POST",
    credentials: "include",
    headers: {
      "Content-Type": "application/json",
      "X-CSRFToken": getCookie("csrftoken")!,
    },
    body: JSON.stringify({ email, password }),
  });
  if (r.status === 401) {
    const body = await r.json();
    if (body.meta?.is_authenticated === false && body.data?.flows) {
      // 2FA required — render the MFA challenge screen.
      return { needsMfa: true };
    }
  }
  if (!r.ok) throw new Error(`Login failed: ${r.status}`);
  return { needsMfa: false };
}
```

See the full [allauth headless API reference](https://docs.allauth.org/en/latest/headless/index.html) for every endpoint.
